Village of Lake Placid
September 3 at 1:51 PM ·

September 3, 2020

ATTENTION ALL LAKE PLACID MUNICIPAL ELECTRIC CUSTOMERS:

All Lake Placid Municipal Electric customers will experience a power interruption that is estimated to last four hours, beginning at Midnight, September 16th and ending at 4:00 a.m. on Thursday, September 17th. Any changes related to the outage will be posted on the Village’s website and Facebook page.

This outage is necessary to transfer the incoming 115 Kilovolt transmission line to a new receiving structure at the Lake Placid Municipal Electric Old Military Road Substation. Should a problem on Lake Placid Municipal Electric owned 115 Kilovolt system occur, recent upgrades should result in fewer customers being affected, for shorter durations of time.

The Lake Placid Municipal Electric Department thanks all customers for their understanding and cooperation.

LAKE PLACID CENTRAL SCHOOL
ZOOM PARENT PUBLIC DISCUSSIONS
Dear Parents: Lake Placid Central School will be having three parent public discussions regarding the school’s reopening plan. Due to the ongoing construction in each building there is not enough space available right now to hold these meetings in person. We are offering three different meeting times that will accommodate your schedule. All meetings will be via Zoom.

Below is the information to join the meeting. Parents will be muted on entry. The question and answer period will follow the presentation. We are asking parents to utilize the raise your hand to ask a question feature in zoom. If at the end of the time all questions are not answered we will utilize the chat feature. You may also send questions to lpdistrictclerk@lpcsd.org for reading during this time.

Please see the schedule and links to these informational sessions on our website. http://www.lpcsd.org/district/coronavirus-update/

post_text:
Dear Lake Placid School Community –

Today the Governor gave all NY schools the green light to reopen. We are excited to see students again in September.

The Governor also asked that each school provide families with the following information, most of which is already posted in our formal reopening plans:
• What is our remote learning plan? In particular, how do we address questions of equity?
• How will we meet the NYS Department of Health guidelines on COVID testing?
• How will we arrange for contact tracing should a student or staff member test positive?

We will be posting specific answers to these questions on our website in the coming days.

In addition, we will be offering three live online discussions about our reopening plans. These are intended to provide parents with information about reopening and answer any questions. We will offer a separate but similar discussion for teachers.

Thank you for your patience and support as we work through the challenges of reopening the Lake Placid Central School District.

Lake Placid Public Library
June 30 at 10:57 AM ·

Our Summer Reading Program is going to look a little different this year, but we invite you to join us as we navigate through some new ways to promote reading throughout the summer! Attached you will find a reading log to print out (or call the library and we'll bring one out to you) to track your reading this summer (see directions). We will have weekly themes, which will be presented by Mrs. Armstrong, and we will post a link to the recording here on Mondays. Each theme will have some book suggestions and a corresponding activities packet which will also be posted. During the week of July 12-July 18 we will provide you with a link to watch a virtual performance by the Traveling Lantern Co. If you have any questions, please email librarian@lakeplacidlibrary.org

The Board of Education, administration, faculty, and staff at Lake Placid CSD would like to thank everyone in the community for supporting our school district and voting to approve the annual budget. Ultimately it is our children who benefit from your support. Thank you!

Here are the final results for …

The Budget:
YES: 930
NO: 240
This represents 79% support for the budget.

The Bus Proposition:
YES: 974
NO : 195

The Wilmington Library:
YES: 1,038
NO : 124

Three Board of Education Seats:
Jeff Brownell, Joan Hallet-Valentine, and Dan Marvin are all re-elected for three-year terms

Results of the Lake Placid Library vote will be reported separately

Again, thank you for all of your support!

post_text:
It's official: Friday, June 12th will be the last day of school for students and staff.

The Board of Education approved final calendar changes at its meeting on Tuesday evening making the last day of school official. Friday, June 12th is now the last day of school, and summer recess will begin after that. We are planning many ways to celebrate the end of this unique school year, including a "Drive-in" graduation ceremony scheduled for Friday, June 26th. Congratulations to our students, families, teachers, and support staff for all you have accomplished during this uncertain time. And thank you for your hard work, patience, and perseverance. Have a wonderful summer!

post_text:
Dear LPCSD Students, Families, and Community Members –

Happy June! To date our staff and faculty have been planning for the end of the school year, with Friday June 12th unofficially scheduled as last day of school for students and staff. On Tuesday the Board of Education will vote on calendar changes making the final day official. We hope there will be no late-breaking changes from the Governor’s office. Summer recess will begin after that. Congratulations to all of our students, staff, and families, for all you have accomplished in the face of so many challenges during this historic and unique school year. Enjoy all of the end-of-year celebrations, banners, signs, and parades honoring students throughout the month of June. We will be working hard to prepare the schools for reopening in the fall, and – fingers crossed – I hope to see everyone back at school in September.

Sincerely,

Dr. Roger Catania, LPCSD Superintendent

The Elementary School's Comic Book Club is hosting an ART CONTEST open to all LPES students in grades 3-5! You can submit a drawing, cartoon, or comic book (more than one page or multiple panels). Scan or take a photo of your entry and email your entry to 28wmcgahay@lakeplacidcsd.net or apaulson@lpcsd.org. Mrs. Philion has agreed to be head judge!

DEADLINE for receiving art is WEDNESDAY, MAY 27! Don't delay emailing your entry!
WINNER ANNOUNCED: Wednesday, June 3
PRIZE: $25 Gift certificate to The Bookstore Plus.

REMEMBER: Please sign your art work (you are the artist, after all) but with your first name and last initial only. The winner's work will be posted on the Comic Book Club website. Good luck!!

For more information, check out the Comic Book Club website:
https://sites.google.com/lakeplacidcsd.net/lpescomicbookclub/cbc-spring-2020

Although Anya was offered merit based scholarships from St Lawrence and University of Rochester and was accepted to RPI, the college she most wants to attend is the University at Buffalo to pursue a Bachelors in Environmental Design. Please join me in congratulating her on her tremendous accomplishments thus far:

4.0 GPA with Membership to the National Honors Society Varsity Cross Country Captain
President of the LPHS Environmental Club
Leader and Speaker at the ADK Youth Climate Program

In addition to all this, she has worked since she was able to get working papers and racked up over 269 hours of volunteer work!

Like all seniors, she is missing many milestones that we all took for granted like Prom, Graduation and Senior Prank Day. If you would like to send her a personal greeting or congratulations you can send them to:

Anya Morgan
987 Bartlett Road
Upper Jay, NY 12987

post_text:
Dear LPCSD Friends and Families —

Our school calendar continues to change in response to the ongoing crisis and the Governor’s executive orders impacting the school year. Because the orders require us to use all remaining vacation and snow days, we will now be in session this Friday, May 22nd. This is a change. All remote learning activities will continue on that day. However, the following Monday, May 25th, is Memorial Day, which is a federal holiday. School is officially closed for the day, so no classes will be held. I encourage everyone to celebrate with flags and family barbecues, and by remembering those who died in service to our country. Happy Memorial Day! And best wishes to everyone as we approach the end of this unique and challenging school year.

Sincerely,

Roger Catania, Superintendent
Lake Placid Central School

Construction Update - Track

The work on the track is scheduled to begin on Tuesday May 26th. During the work day the track will be closed. Use in the evening will be permissible following the posted rules.

Near the end of June the track surface will be refinished and closed completely for about 2-3 weeks to let it cure.

Thank you for your patience during this time.

Dear Parents,

We know how tough it is to take on the task of helping and monitoring your child’s online learning, especially with learning the technology that comes with it. We hope to ease some of your burden by offering a Parent Tech Hour on Tuesdays from 11:00 – 12:00 on Zoom where you can ask any questions you have to Ms. Lindsay, MS Principal, and Ms. Patenaude, MHS Librarian. Anything from how to turn in an assignment to learning a new website to navigate, we are here for you. If you're not available at this time, feel free to contact us for an appointment. Zoom link is available on the MHS Newsletter.

Thank you,
Kaitlin Patenaude, Librarian

post_text:
Stay Safe, Play Safe

As a precautionary measure to slow the spread of Coronavirus (COVID-19), the Lake Placid Central School District has closed down the playground at the Elementary School. The track at the Kordziel Fields (Horseshow Grounds) will remain open for now with the understanding that users comply with social distancing requirements: remain 6 feet apart (including children) and do not gather in groups. It is also important to follow the rules on the sign - NO DOGS ALLOWED, NO WHEELED BIKES ON THE TRACK, ETC.

Stay safe and healthy everyone!

As a precautionary measure to slow the spread of Coronavirus (COVID-19), the Lake Placid Central School District has closed down the playground at the Elementary School. The track at the Kordziel Fields (Horseshow Grounds) will remain open for now with the understanding that users comply with social distancing requirements: remain 6 feet apart (including children) and do not gather in groups. It is also important to follow the rules on the sign - NO DOGS ALLOWED, NO WHEELED BIKES ON THE TRACK, ETC.

Stay safe and healthy everyone!

post_text:
Dear LPCSD Families —

The Governor’s Executive Order has directed all school districts to continue alternative instructional options during the period we had originally set aside for spring break (April 6 – April 17). Today I want to let you know how we intend to alter our approach to at-home learning throughout this 2-week period. Each school has developed a project-based activity or series of activities that we hope will provide students and families with a more engaging and creative approach to learning. During this time we hope that students will read, think, create, get outside, and set aside their devices for at least a part of the day. Schools will make sure that expectations are appropriate for every age and grade level, and that teachers and support staff will be available to help and guide students along the way. You can expect more details from the principals at each school. We hope that your families are healthy and safe. Thanks to all of you for your feedback, encouragement, and support.

Sincerely,

Dr. Roger P. Catania
Superintendent of Schools

The Lake Placid School District would like to thank EVERYONE for their generous donations to our food backpack program. Our first delivery went out today which included all of the food donated by members of our community, as well as fresh produce that was donated by ORDA and Northwood School. If you would still like to donate, we are accepting gift cards to Hannaford, Price Chopper and Aldi in any denomination. This will allow families to grab other items like diapers, baby food, meats, produce and needed cleaning supplies.

Again, THANK YOU for supporting our students and for your understanding as we navigate these challenging times.

This will allow families to grab other items like diapers, baby food, meats, produce and needed cleaning supplies.

Again, THANK YOU for supporting our students and for your understanding as we navigate these challenging times.

post_text:
Thank you all for the generous outpouring of support for the kids of our community. Many people have asked about getting food to supplement our food distribution. Our Backpack Coordinator has put together a list of items that would help with this situation. The food can be dropped at the main office in the MS/HS to be distributed to all of the elementary, middle and high school students in need. We appreciate your extreme generosity, but ask you to please limit donations to the food items listed below:

Spaghetti
Canned spaghetti sauce
Peanut Butter
Jelly
Bread or English muffins
Canned pasta (ravioli, spaghetti-o, etc)
Mac and cheese (please only the cheese sauce type; requiring no milk or butter)
Ramen noodles
Ramen soup
Granola Bars
Pop tarts
Cheeze-its or goldfish type crackers
Individual cheese or peanut butter crackers
Pretzels
Apples and oranges

Thank you for understanding and thank you for your support. What an amazing community we live in!!

Ms. Theresa Lindsay
Lake Placid Central School
Middle School Principal

FROM Elementary School

As each of you have heard, we are closing our doors to students until after the spring break in an attempt to slow the spread of this virus. Teachers will be in their classrooms tomorrow - Monday March 16 - (8:30am-3:30pm) so that you and your child may come to school to get any needed supplies, including devices. As has been explained to your child, education is expected to continue through creative means. Please support your child's education by providing them a quiet, structured space to work through the material provided by their teacher. Teachers will continue to be available to answer questions, offer guidance and provide feedback on all work completed. Their individual contact information is provided with the materials they have prepared. Thank you for your patience as we all work through this unique time.

Sonja Franklin
Elementary Principal

Lake Placid, NY 12946

post_text:
This message went out on One Call beginning at 11:00 a.m. on March 15, 2020.

Lake Placid Central School will be closed starting Monday, March 16th and will remain closed through the end of spring break. Faculty and staff will report on Monday to organize at-home instruction, and students should expect to continue their classes and subjects through distance learning opportunities on Tuesday. We expect to reopen in-person instruction on Monday, April 20th. Although we have no known cases of COVID-19, we are closing as part of a widespread effort to slow the spread of the new coronavirus, and we are doing so on the recommendation of county health departments and in coordination with school districts throughout the region. More details will be forthcoming through email and on our website. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we navigate these challenging and uncertain times

post_text:
We are winding down the regular seasons for winter sports, which also means recognizing the seniors for their dedication to their sport. Here is the plan for senior nights:

Boys Hockey: 2/18 at the SLCC before the start of the game vs. Plattsburgh (Game starts at 6:30)

Boys Basketball: 2/10 vs. Schroon Lake: Before the start of the Varsity Game (About 7:00)

Girls Basketball: 2/12 vs. Boquet Valley: Before the start of the Varsity Game (About 7:00)

Nordic Skiing: 2/13 vs. Saranac Lake at Mt. Van Hoevenberg - final day of sectionals

Girls Hockey had their senior night last month and Alpine Skiing has no seniors this year.

John Burdick
LPCSD Athletic Director

post_text: Thank you Hill and Hollow Music of Saranac, NY for bringing Alexis Chartrand and Nicoloas Babineau for three amazing one hour sessions of Traditional Québecois Music and history! Through performance and interactive demonstration, High School and the 6th grade French classes learned first hand traditional techniques of fiddle, call and response singing as well as podorythmie (foot tapping). Merci Alexis et Nicolas!
text: Thank you Hill and Hollow Music of Saranac, NY for bringing Alexis Chartrand and Nicoloas Babineau for three amazing one hour sessions of Traditional Québecois Music and history! Through performance and interactive demonstration, High School and the 6th grade French classes learned first hand traditional techniques of fiddle, call and response singing as well as podorythmie (foot tapping). Merci Alexis et Nicolas!
